<div class="text" id="3.2.1.1">
<span class="pagehead">CES Press Releases :: Press Release Detail</span><br><br>



<span class="subhead">17 Pavilions Highlight the Advances of Consumer Electronics at the 2002 CES</span>

	<br><br>
	<b>Digital Entertainment Village to Display the Hottest Technologies in Gaming, Music and Imaging</b>

<br><br>		
<strong><i>Arlington, Virginia&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/12/2001</i></strong>
<br><br>
Seventeen pavilions will display the best and newest technologies in the consumer electronics industry when the 2002 International CES returns to the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC) in Las Vegas, Nev., January 8-11.<p>

A host of pavilions will address a number of hot sectors in the industry including gaming, wireless, digital audio and video, and mobile products among others.  The line-up of 2002 CES pavilions are as follows:<p>

<b>Wi-Fi Pavilion</b><br>
Located in the upper level of the new South Hall expansion of the LVCC, the Wi-Fi Pavilion, sponsored by the Wireless Ethernet Compatability Alliance (WECA), aims to promote Wi-Fi as the global, wireless LAN standard across all market segments.  The Wi-Fi Pavilion includes a test suite that defines how member products are tested to certify they are interoperable with other Wi-Fi-certified products.  This test will assure that products bearing the Wi-Fi logo will work with each other.<p>

<b>Bluetooth Showcase</b><br>
Bluetooth wireless technology enables two-way transmission of data, making efficient, fast, flawless wireless connections a reality. The rapid widespread acceptance of Bluetooth-enabled wireless technology across the wide spectrum of telecommunications, computer hardware/software, automotive, military, medical and consumer electronics industries promises improvements in the products that we use for work and play. CES attendees will get to see this new technology in-depth at the Bluetooth Pavilion, sponsored by the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG), located in the new LVCC South Hall.  ADD Value Communications, ATO Technology, Hewlett-Packard, Microtune, Motorola, 3Com and Uniwill are just a few companies on display at the Bluetooth Showcase.<p>

<b>CES Federal IT Pavilion</b><br>
The International CES has partnered with National Conference Services Inc. (NCSI) to produce the first CES Federal IT Pavilion.  The pavilion will be held January 7-9, 2002 in the Royale Ballroom at the Riviera Hotel in Las Vegas, Nevada.  The 2002 CES Federal IT Pavilion will feature more than 100 industry leading companies exhibiting the latest in emerging technologies to more than 2,000 key and decision makers from the intelligence community, Department of Defense and other federal civilian agencies.  The pavilion will showcase emerging technologies supporting new military and homeland defense strategies to combat conventional and cyber-based terrorism.<p>

<b>Digital Entertainment Village</b><br>
The Digital Entertainment Village combines interactive entertainment, digital audio and technological imaging advances all located in the upper level South Hall of the LVCC.  The following three pavilions comprise the Digital Entertainment Village:<p>

<b>The Gaming and Interactive Entertainment Pavilion</b><br>
Electronic gaming and interactive entertainment are colliding. Sponsored by ieMagazine, the Gaming and Interactive Entertainment Zone will showcase the most comprehensive line-up of entertainment platforms and distribution channels. In conjunction with the pavilion and bringing the top names in gaming to the show, the Interactive Entertainment Merchants Association (IEMA) will hold its Board meeting at CES on January 8.  Companies participating in this pavilion include Gameinis Limited, ProMax Wireless Products and Xgaming Inc.<p>

<b>MP3 and Internet Audio Zone</b><br>
MP3 has become the commonly accepted term for one of the many compression algorithms, also known as codecs, available for downloading digital music files from the Internet.  The MP3 and Internet Audio Zone will focus on the convergence of the entertainment, computer and Internet industries by showcasing the hottest audio products for the Internet.  Daisy Technology, Echo Mobile Music, Lasonic, Octiv, Remote Solution and Smart Media are a few companies participating in the MP3 and Internet Audio Zone.<p>

<b>Imaging Technology Pavilion</b><br>
Sponsored by Photo Trade News, the Imaging Technology Pavilion will bring attendees up-to-speed on the latest video hardware, convergence devices, photo/video editing and processor hardware/software, digital storage media/readers, photo printers and imaging devices, digital/video accessories, processing/storage services and multimedia publishing/Internet solutions driving content and delivery of digital images and video.  Some companies participating in the Imaging Technology Pavilion include Pacific Image Electronics, SmartDisk Corp., Soundvision and Wynit Inc.<p>

<b>Digital Car Showroom</b><br>
The Digital Car Showroom, located in the LVCC North Hall, will allow attendees to see and test the latest mobile technologies.  Visitors to the showroom will learn about new vehicle navigation tools, entertainment systems, safety devices, obstacle warning systems, and how the impact of wireless technology has connected them all.  Some of the companies participating in the Digital Car Showroom, sponsored by the Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) include Infomove, Pacific Rim Technologies, Tesla Electronics, Thales Navigation and Trav Route.<p>

<b>IDB Forum</b><br>
The Intelligent Transportation System Data Bus (IDB) defines the industry's first set of interface standards for automotive information, communications and entertainment systems.  Located in the North Hall of the LVCC, the IDB Forum will educate attendees on the convergence standard for electronics equipment in the new-generation automotive systems that IDB provides.  The IDB Forum will showcase leading automobile manufacturers and key engineers ready to discuss the latest innovations in aftermarket car products.<p>

<b>DVD-R/RW Pavilion from RWPPI</b><br>
The latest DVD-R/RW recording hardware and blank media is showcased at the DVD-R/RW Pavilion.  The RW Products Promotion Initiative (RWPPI) has brought together companies such as Kenwood, Pioneer, Samsung, Sharp, Sony and Thomson to display these new technologies.<p>

<b>Energy Efficiency Center</b><br>
For the first time at CES, the Energy Efficiency Center will include products that either promote energy efficiency or are energy efficient.  In partnership with the Environmental Protection Agency's Energy Star program, the Energy Efficiency Center will be located in the lower level of the LVCC South Hall.  Attendees can test products to see how energy efficient they really are.  Organizations include BeAtHome, EPA, Intel, Panasonic and Sony.<p>

<b>HomePNA Pavilion</b><br>
HomePNA (Home Phoneline Networking Alliance) will present the ease of networking the home using a single, unified phoneline networking industry standard.  HomePNA started with 11 companies and now has grown to more than 150 companies including those representing the networking, telecommunications, hardware, software and consumer electronics industries.  The HomePNA Pavilion will be located in the upper level of the LVCC South Hall.<p>

<b>The Digital Home Appliance Pavilion</b><br>
Located in the lower level of the LVCC South Hall, the Digital Home Appliance Pavilion will showcase products that are at the core of the networked home. Here you will see a focused effort on the products and technology for Internet-ready appliances.  Companies include Broadmax Technologies, COMMAX, DoBox, First2Hit, Home Automated Living, Home Automation Inc. and Tonight's Menu.<p>

<b>Emerging Technologies Launchpad</b><br>
Next-generation consumer electronics products will light up the lower level of the LVCC South Hall at the Emerging Technologies Launchpad, sponsored by Fortune Magazine.  This pavilion displays the latest consumer technology innovations and the companies responsible for designing them.  Some companies exhibiting in this pavilion include Azuradisc, Concealed Entertainment, Hidden Camera Solutions, Natural Life, Novation Products and Vividlogic Inc.<p>

<b>Palm Solutions Providers Pavilion</b><br>
The Palm Solutions Providers Pavilion, located in the LVCC South Hall upper level, showcases the latest Palm accessories, software and hardware.  Act!, Corex/CardScan, Compex, Globalstar, Seiko Instruments and Vision Objects are just a few of the companies participating in this pavilion.<p>

<b>SD Card Association Pavilion</b><br>
As demand for new digital technology applications reaches critical mass, memory storage will be a question pertinent to the global business as well as the local teenager. The SD Card offers a combination of high storage capacity, fast data transfer, flexibility and security. The SD Card Pavilion, sponsored by the SD Card Association, will be located in the LVCC South Hall upper level.<p>

<b>Sony Memory Stick Pavilion</b><br>
The Sony Memory Stick is flash memory and storage, plus more, with its goal to be the universal media for digital transfer and exchange. The Memory Stick Pavilion, located in the Central Hall of the LVCC, will feature more than 50 companies with current and future products utilizing the format for flash memory and storage.<p>

<b>Security and Contingency Planning Pavilion</b><br>
Located in the South Hall upper level of the LVCC, this pavilion will feature the newest safety and security products available.  Products will include security technologies for the business and the home.  Mansoor and Taser International are just a few companies participating in this pavilion.<p>

For more news on CES before, during and after the show, visit www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>

ABOUT CEA<br>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) represents more than 650 U.S. companies involved in the design, development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, wireless and landline communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, CEA's members account for more than $70 billion in annual sales.  CEA's resources are available online at www.CE.org, the definitive source for information about the consumer electronics industry.<p>

CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.

<br><br>
</div>
